y imitated the exact acts of violence on the doll, notably the kicking demonstrated in the video. Those in the non-aggression group did not perform acts of violence as frequently. Interestingly, when the gender of the aggressive adult matched that of the child, the frequency of violent attacks increased; boys watching aggressive males were more violent than those who watched women, and girls watching aggressive women participated in more verbal and physical attacks than those who watched men.%0a%3c %0a%3c This experiment makes me wonder, does a guardian's manner of language affect a child? For example, if a parent always spoke passively, would that stylistically affect how that child spoke as they grew older? Or more directly, if a parent always used profanity in an aggressive tone would that create an angrier child? In an experimental study, a longitudinal study would tell us. But of course, children are not doomed by their caretaker's behavior. While a child's environment inevitably affects them, we know it does not define them. %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
